   =20
      Insider hacking
   =20
 =20
If you hack into a company=E2=80=99s computers and steal its earnings relea=
se=C2=A0before it=E2=80=99s public, and then you trade the company=E2=80=99=
s stock based on the earnings release, is that insider trading? There is an=
 argument that it isn=E2=80=99t: You are not an=C2=A0insider, you had no du=
ty of trust and confidence to the company, you just hacked into its compute=
rs and stole inside information. By the letter of the Securities and Exchan=
ge Commission=E2=80=99s insider trading rule, it would seem that you are no=
t guilty of insider trading.My slightly more expansive view of the matter i=
s that =E2=80=9Cinsider trading=E2=80=9D means (1) trading on material nonp=
ublic information that (2) you got in a bad way. Getting material nonpublic=
 information by hacking is clearly a bad way to get it, so you insider trad=
ed. This is, I think, fairly intuitive. We have talked a  couple of  times =
about an insider trading bill that has been proposed in Congress and passed=
 the=C2=A0House of Representatives that uses this intuitive standard (=E2=
=80=9Cobtained wrongfully=E2=80=9D), but it is not yet the law.So it=E2=80=
=99s a bit murky but, you know, don=E2=80=99t actually do this. Even if it =
is not =E2=80=9Cinsider trading,=E2=80=9D you=E2=80=99re gonna get in troub=
le for it. Insider trading is not a separate crime; it is a variety of secu=
rities fraud, a violation of Section 10(b) of the Exchange Act, which prohi=
bits using =E2=80=9Cany manipulative or deceptive device=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9C=
in connection with the purchase or sale of any security,=E2=80=9D and of Ru=
le 10b-5, which prohibits using =E2=80=9Cany device, scheme, or artifice to=
 defraud =E2=80=A6=C2=A0in connection with the purchase or sale of any secu=
rity.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Insider trading is just treated as a kind of =E2=80=9Cm=
anipulative or deceptive device.=E2=80=9D But so is hacking, probably. If i=
t=E2=80=99s not insider trading, it=E2=80=99s exactly as bad as insider tra=
ding and prohibited by exactly the same statute.=C2=A0 We talked way back i=
n 2015 about some hackers who hacked into the news wires =E2=80=94=C2=A0the=
 services that store companies=E2=80=99 press releases before they are rele=
ased =E2=80=94=C2=A0and got thousands of earnings releases early, and then =
sold those earnings releases to traders who used them to make money. =E2=80=
=9CBig hacker insider trading charges,=E2=80=9D I called them. Were they? T=
wo traders were convicted of securities fraud based on this, and they appea=
led, and on Monday the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit decided=
 the appeals.[1] One of the traders argued that he could not have committed=
 securities fraud:To challenge his convictions on these substantive securit=
ies fraud counts, Korchevsky first argues that the government could not pro=
ve he engaged in a =E2=80=9Cscheme or artifice to defraud=E2=80=9D within t=
he meaning of Rule 10b-5. Specifically, he claims the proof necessarily fai=
led because he did not owe a fiduciary duty to investors or potential inves=
tors in the companies whose press releases were stolen, and because any dec=
eption employed to obtain the releases did not target the investors. Second=
, Korchevsky argues that the type of=C2=A0computer hacking used to access M=
arketwired=E2=80=99s systems=E2=80=94the conduct charged in Count Four=E2=
=80=94did not constitute a =E2=80=9Cdeceptive device or contrivance=E2=80=
=9D within the meaning of Section 10(b).The Second Circuit disagreed:First,=
 we dispatch Korchevsky=E2=80=99s contention that he did not engage in a =
=E2=80=9Cscheme or artifice to defraud.=E2=80=9D Although a fiduciary duty =
is relevant to other securities violations=E2=80=94e.g., insider trading=E2=
=80=94it need not be shown to prove the securities fraud charged here: frau=
dulent trading in securities by an outsider.=C2=A0Further, Korchevsky=E2=80=
=99s assertion that the deception must have targeted investors contradicts =
the plain language of Rule 10b-5. The deception need only be =E2=80=9Cin co=
nnection with the purchase or sale of any security,=E2=80=9D and here it wa=
s. The newswire hacking directly prompted and enabled the charged securitie=
s trading. Indeed, the ensuing trades needed to occur soon after a press re=
lease was illicitly obtained from=C2=A0a newswire=E2=80=99s servers, but be=
fore the newswire could publish the release, in order to maximize the hacke=
d information=E2=80=99s value.Second, we find that the hack of Marketwired=
=E2=80=99s systems qualified as a =E2=80=9Cdeceptive device or contrivance=
=E2=80=9D under Section 10(b). ...=C2=A0Every time the hackers attempted to=
 access parts of the system by entering stolen credentials, they misreprese=
nted themselves to be authorized users. =E2=80=9C[M]isrepresenting one=E2=
=80=99s identity in order to gain access to information that is otherwise o=
ff limits, and then stealing that information is plainly =E2=80=98deceptive=
=E2=80=99 within the ordinary meaning of the word.=E2=80=9DThe logic there =
feels a little strange =E2=80=94=C2=A0they deceived Marketwired, which allo=
wed them to make money from=C2=A0investors; all in all they did securities =
fraud, but don=E2=80=99t ask=C2=A0who=C2=A0they defrauded =E2=80=94=C2=A0un=
til you remember that it=E2=80=99s exactly the logic of insider trading. =
=E2=80=9CInsider trading is not about fairness, it=E2=80=99s about theft,=
=E2=80=9D I  often  say: In insider trading, you get in trouble for the com=
bination of (1) betraying your duty of confidence to the owner of the infor=
mation (your employer, your  golf buddy, etc.) and (2) using the informatio=
n to make money by trading stock with strangers. You are I suppose doing a =
securities fraud on the people who trade with you, but you=E2=80=99re not r=
eally deceiving them; it=E2=80=99s the combination of betraying one person =
and making money from another that creates insider trading. Same with hacki=
ng-based insider trading. Which I am going to continue to call =E2=80=9Cins=
ider trading=E2=80=9D even if the Second Circuit doesn=E2=80=99t.
 =20
   =20
      Wall Street culture
   =20
 =20
My shameful secret vice is I basically agree  with this:There=E2=80=99s a r=
eason junior bankers just starting out on Wall Street work 12-hour days, si=
x days a week, says Mary Erdoes, chief executive officer of JPMorgan Chase =
& Co.=E2=80=99s asset and wealth management business. ...=C2=A0In an episod=
e of =E2=80=9CBloomberg Wealth with David Rubenstein,=E2=80=9D she invoked =
the concept that it takes 10,000 hours of practice and devotion to compete =
at an elite level.=E2=80=9CIf you think 10,000 hours is about what you need=
 to master any subject, if someone comes in and has a regular, eight-hour-a=
-day job, five days a week, it=E2=80=99s gonna take about five years to hav=
e a base-level mastery,=E2=80=9D she said to Rubenstein, the co-founder of =
Carlyle Group, on Bloomberg TV. =E2=80=9COn Wall Street, it=E2=80=99s more =
like 12 hours a day, six days a week. That cuts you down to about two and a=
 half years before you become mastered in something.=E2=80=9DYeah it=E2=80=
=99s fine. I think you probably do get better, faster, at making leveraged =
buyout models if you do it 80 hours a week instead of 40 hours a week, and =
that is useful both for you and for your employer.I also think, though, tha=
t there is a signaling benefit to it that is almost detached from the conte=
nt. If you go to Wall Street and spend two years working 80 or 100-hour wee=
ks building LBO models, and everyone knows that that=E2=80=99s how it works=
, then people will assume that your LBO-model-building skills are=C2=A0impr=
essive. Not just that you=E2=80=99re good at building LBO models, I mean, b=
ut also that that=E2=80=99s a fancy skill to have. =E2=80=9COh, wow, you ha=
ve mastered a skill that requires years of grueling labor and total commitm=
ent,=E2=80=9D they will say. Then they will hire you for some job that=C2=
=A0doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0require building LBO models, because they assume th=
at=C2=A0you=E2=80=99re smart and knowledgeable,=C2=A0or they will pay=C2=A0=
your bank lots of money to advise on their merger, because they assume that=
 the bank has arcane and hard-to-acquire skills. Whereas if you spent 40 ho=
urs a week building LBO models everyone would be like =E2=80=9Cmeh that can=
=E2=80=99t be that hard.=E2=80=9D None of this has anything to do with what=
 goes into an LBO model; it=E2=80=99s just about the hours that you (ostent=
atiously) work.I have  written=C2=A0recently about the tension between the =
old model of Wall Street analyst programs as sort of a universal finishing =
school for smart ambitious people, versus a gentler model of Wall Street an=
alyst programs as just a normal job. If it=E2=80=99s an elite finishing sch=
ool =E2=80=94=C2=A0like a medical residency =E2=80=94=C2=A0then I suppose i=
t should be 80 hours a week; becoming elite is hard, and not for just anyon=
e. If it=E2=80=99s just a job then, you know, sure, take the weekend off,  =
play a sport, whatever. I think that if you are entering a Wall Street anal=
yst program, you probably want to take the weekend off (I sure do!), but=C2=
=A0also want it to retain its mystique as an elite finishing school. Those =
things are in tension.
